l but won't really have their questions answered because... &#10;A child with issues will be coddled, nurtured, and hand-held through the material they need to know to pass a standardized test. Retention isn't important. &#10;They ignore the exceptional kids, who end up being the discipline problems because they are bored out of their skulls. &#10;Gone are the days when they would put kids in different classes based on aptitude. That hurts feelings and encourages resentment, or some such nonsense. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="786" language="en" documentId="4755" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Fonceai" date="2nd November 2006 04:32 PM" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.volconvo.com/forums/showthread.php?t=12481&amp;page=3" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4755" notes="" title="Public Schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="31"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="32" end="103"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="104" end="243"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="244" end="355"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="356" end="512"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="513" end="632"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="633" end="786"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63"/></xmi:XMI>